Statutory homelessness

Department:
Department for Communities and Local Government
Published:
10 October 2017
Last updated:
11 October 2017, see all updates
Source:
Homelessness statistics
Area covered:
England
Time period:
2006/07 to 2016/17

The main facts and figures show that:

  • in 2016/17 local authorities in England had a duty to find accommodation for 59,100 households that included dependent children or vulnerable people and were in most cases threatened with the loss of, or unable to live in, their current accommodation – but not necessarily sleeping rough (in this measure ‘homeless households’ refers to this type of homelessness only, known as 'statutory homelessness')

  • ethnic minorities account for 33% of homeless households

  • 16% of all homeless households were Black, 9% were Asian, 3% were from a Mixed ethnic background and 5% were from the Other ethnic minority group (ethnicity wasn't known for 6% of homeless households)

  • London had the highest overall number of homeless households and the highest percentage of homeless households made up of ethnic minorities (not including White ethnic minorities) – this may be because these ethnic groups make up a higher percentage of London’s population

  • in 2016/17, there were 3 homeless households for every 1,000 households in England, and 5 for every 1,000 households in London (outside of London it was 2 per 1,000)

  • the London borough with the highest number of homeless households per 1,000 households was Newham (10 per 1,000), where the majority of homeless households were Asian (35%)

Things you need to know

These figures only relate to statutory homelessness, which requires a household to be unintentionally homeless and demonstrate a priority category need (such as dependent children). It therefore doesn’t include single homeless people without specific vulnerabilities, nor does it account for those who don’t approach their local authority for help.

Much of the data at the local authority level is excluded because there are fewer than 5 homeless households in each ethnic group. This information is not available as there is a risk of disclosing personal information.

Homelessness data is collected and reported every 3 months by local authorities in England. However, these more detailed statistics on statutory homelessness by ethnicity across local authorities in England are reported annually. This means less data needs to be excluded in order to avoid disclosing individuals’ identities.

The ethnicity recorded is that of the person within the household making the homelessness application. Ethnicity was unknown for 6% of households.

What the data measures

For the purposes of this measure a ‘homeless household’ refers to a household which the local authority has a duty to house in settled accommodation because its members are unintentionally homeless and in a priority need category, but not sleeping rough. Government calls this ‘statutory homelessness’. Priority need cases are those with dependent children (around two-thirds of cases) or those who have a specific vulnerability such as a disability or experience of domestic violence.

This data measures the number of homeless households for each ethnic group between financial years 2006/07 and 2016/17.

It also measures the percentage of all homeless households that each ethnic group accounts for. In 2016/17, there were 59,100 homeless households.

The figures are based on administrative data published in the Department of Communities and Local Government’s Live tables on homelessness

To provide additional context, the downloads include statistics on the rate of homelessness per 1000 of the population has been included for each area using population estimates (2015) published by the Office for National Statistics.

The ethnic categories used in this data

For this data, ethnicity is broken down into the following broad categories:

  • White
  • Black or Black British
  • Asian or Asian British
  • Mixed
  • Chinese or Other
  • Not stated

Data on statutory homelessness was collected using more specific ethnic groups from 2006 to 2013, but since then only with the broad ethnic groups. This is because data was collected at the local authority level, where some specific ethnic groups included such small numbers that individuals might be identified. These particular broad groupings were chosen because they make comparisons easier between more recent years and earlier ones.

Summary

In these points, 'homeless households' refers only to households that local authorities in England had a duty to find accommodation for because those households included dependent children or vulnerable people and were, in most cases, threatened with the loss of, or unable to live in, their current accommodation (but were not necessarily sleeping rough).

This data shows that:

  • the 2016/17 homelessness figure of 59,100 households was up 2% from the previous year but down 19% from 2006/07

  • 35,890 homeless households in 2016/17 were White, 9,330 were Black, 5,560 were Asian, 1,990 were from a Mixed ethnic background and 2,820 were from the Other ethnic minority group (ethnicity wasn't known for 3,510 households)

  • White households saw the largest increase in the number of homeless households between 2015/16 and 2016/17 – an additional 1,690 households or a 5% increase

  • the number of Black households and Mixed households that were homeless fell by 2% between 2015/16 and 2016/17 (a decrease of 210 Black households and 30 Mixed households)

  • the number of homeless households in England for Asian and Other ethnic groups is currently at its highest level it has been in the last ten years

  • the highest number of White homeless households over the last ten years was 54,370 in 2006/07

  • the highest number for Black and Mixed homeless households over the last ten years was 9,540 and 2,020 respectively, both in 2015/16

Data withheld to protect confidentiality

Summary

In these points, 'homeless households' refers only to households that local authorities in England had a duty to find accommodation for because those households included dependent children or vulnerable people and were, in most cases, threatened with the loss of, or unable to live in, their current accommodation (but were not necessarily sleeping rough).

This data shows that:

  • in 2016/17, there were 3 homeless households for every 1,000 households in England, and 5 for every 1,000 households in London (outside London there were 2 homeless households per 1,000 households)

  • in London, the 3 boroughs with the highest number of homeless households per 1,000 households were Newham (10 per 1,000), Enfield (8 per 1,000) and Waltham Forest (8 per 1,000)

  • in Newham, the majority of homeless households were Asian (35%), in Enfield the majority were Black (45%), and in Waltham Forest the majority were either White or Black (34% each)

  • outside of London, the 3 local authorities with the highest number of homeless households per 1,000 households were Peterborough in the East of England (8 per 1,000), Birmingham in the West Midlands (8 per 1,000) and Milton Keynes in the South East (7 per 1,000)

  • in these areas, White households made up the majority of homeless households - Peterborough (74%), Birmingham (33%) and Milton Keynes (53%)

Methodology and type of data

Type of data

Administrative data

Purpose of data source

The P1E form provides the data for published National Statistics on statutory homelessness

Methodology

All local authorities submit a quarterly return summarising at aggregate level their administrative information on homelessness acceptances in their area, covering ethnicity as well as reason for loss of last home, reason for priority need, and use of temporary accommodation.

For more information about the data quality and validation of these homelessness statitics see the technical notes in the homelessness statistical release .

Rounding

Figures in the charts and tables are rounded to the nearest whole number. Figures in the downloads are rounded to 1dp.

Further technical information

See technical notes in the homelessness statistical release .

Data source details

Source

Homelessness statistics

Department

Department for Communities and Local Government

Type of statistic

National Statistics

Publication frequency

Quarterly

Suppression rules

Any values based on fewer than five responses have been suppressed to avoid disclosing personal information. Financial years have been shown rather than quarterly values to minimise suppression.

Disclosure control

Any values based on fewer than five responses have been suppressed to avoid disclosing personal information.
